✅ Primary cammands
*************************
ls -     its show all files that inside the directory
ls -al  -it's show hiddin files in directory
cd       [change directory ] its use for change the present directory
pwd     -it's show whare we are working
cd home -directory will change into home
touch <file-name>  - to create a file

1. File & Directory Commandls
***********************************
ls– List files and directories
pwd – Show the current directory path
cd [directory] – Change directory
mkdir [directory] – Create a new directory
rm [file] – Delete a file
rm -r [directory] – Delete a directory and its contents
cp [source] [destination] – Copy a file or folder
mv [source] [destination] – Move or rename a file/folder

2. File Viewing Commands
*****************************
cat [file] – Show the content of a file
less [file] – View a file page by page
head [file] – Show the first 10 lines of a file
tail [file] – Show the last 10 lines of a file

3. User & Permission Commands
*******************************
whoami – Show the current user
who – Show all logged-in users
chmod [permissions] [file] – Change file permissions
chown [user]:[group] [file] – Change file owner

4. Process Management Commands
**********************************
ps – Show running processes
top – Show real-time system usage
kill [PID] – Kill a process by its ID
pkill [process-name] – Kill a process by name
5. Networking Commands
ifconfig or ip a – Show network details
ping [website] – Check network connectivity
wget [URL] – Download a file from the internet

6. Package Management Commands
******************************************
apt install [package] (Debian/Ubuntu) – Install software
yum install [package] (RHEL/CentOS) – Install software
dnf install [package] (Fedora) – Install software
7. Other Useful Commands
clear – Clear the terminal
history – Show previously used commands
echo "Hello" – Print text to the terminal
uname -a – Show system information
Here are some common Git commands:

 7.Navigation
**************************************
1. cd - Change directory
Example: cd Documents
2. cd ~ - Go to home directory
3. cd .. - Go to parent directory
4. pwd - Print working directory

 8 .File Management
**********************************************
1. ls - List files and directories
Example: ls -l
2. mkdir - Make a new directory
Example: mkdir MyFolder
3. rm - Remove a file or directory
Example: rm myfile.txt
4. cp - Copy a file or directory
Example: cp myfile.txt MyFolder
5. mv - Move or rename a file or directory
Example: mv myfile.txt MyFolder

 9 .File Editing
*******************************************************
1. nano - Open a file in the nano editor
Example: nano myfile.txt
2. vim - Open a file in the vim editor
Example: vim myfile.txt
3. echo - Write text to a file
Example: echo "Hello World!" > myfile.txt

10 . System Information
*******************************************************
1. uname -a - Display system information
2. hostname - Display the system's hostname
3. whoami - Display the current username
4. date - Display the current date and time

11 . User Management
********************************************************
1. sudo - Run a command with superuser privileges
Example: sudo apt-get install firefox
2. su - Switch to the superuser account
3. useradd - Add a new user account
Example: useradd myuser
4. passwd - Change a user's password
Example: passwd myuser

